Which of the following was/were the reasons of Indigo Revolt of 1859-60 in India: 1.Peasants were forced to enter into fraudulent contracts. 2.The price paid for the indigo was far below the market price. 3.The peasants were forced to grow indigo on the most fertile lands. Select the correct answer using the code given below.,1 and 2 only,3 only,"1, 2 and 3",2 only,3,"The most militant and widespread of the peasant movements was the Indigo Revolt of 1859-60.
1.The planters forced the peasants to take ameager amount as advance and enter into fraudulent contracts which, often he was not in a position to repay. The advance was used by the planters to compel them to go on cultivating indigo.
2.The price paid for the indigo plants was far below the market price.
3.The peasant was forced to grow indigo on the best land he had whether or not he wanted to devote his land and labour to more paying crops like rice.
4.At the time of delivery, he was cheated even of the due low price. He also had to pay regular bribes to the planters officials.
5.Since the enforcement of forced and fraudulent contracts through the courts was a difficult and prolonged process, the planters resorted to a reign of terror to coerce the peasants.
6.With a few exceptions, the magistrates, mostly European, favoured the planters with whom they dined and hunted regularly. Those few who tried to be fair were soon transferred.",Hint 76,1,1
